and"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epineal gland\u003C/strong\u003E is a small endocrine gland located in the brain that produces and secretes melatonin. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypothalamus\u003C/strong\u003E, while important in coordinating many endocrine functions, does not produce melatonin. The \u003Cstrong\u003Epituitary gland\u003C/strong\u003E secretes various hormones but not melatonin. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eadrenal gland\u003C/strong\u003E produces stress hormones and mineralocorticoids. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ethyroid gland\u003C/strong\u003E produces thyroid hormones.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EMelatonin synthesis occurs in response to darkness, with production suppressed by light exposure through signals from the retina via the suprachiasmatic nucleus. This hormone helps regulate the sleep-wake cycle, with levels typically rising in the evening and falling in the morning.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The pineal gland synthesizes and secretes melatonin in response to darkness","Melatonin regulates circadian rhythms and sleep-wake cycles","Melatonin production is suppressed by light exposure through retinal signals"],"references":["Arendt J, Aulinas A. Physiology of the Pineal Gland and Melatonin. [Updated 2022 Oct 30]. In: Feingold KR, Anawalt B, Blackman MR, et al., editors. Endotext [Internet]. South Dartmouth (MA): MDText.com, Inc.; 2000-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK550972/","Kovacs, W. J., \u0026 Ojeda, S. R. (Eds.). (2012). Textbook of endocrine physiology. OUP USA.","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52299"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15529"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"item